Introduction

This page provides useful information on the derivation production and its organisation. Please refer to this page for information on the p-tags you should be using for your analysis, on how to submit MC production and request data production, on data obsolescence, useful links and meetings, etc.

  • The page primarily refers to release 21 and Run 3 (R25). For older releases please see here: DerivationProductionTeamPre21
  • For Run-1 DPD production go to DPDProductionTeam

Latest NEWS

  • The latest bulk PHYS+PHYSLITE Run-2 and Run-3 data/MC production is made with 25.0.26.
  • The previous bulk production, still available, is with 25.0.19. For up-to-date details, check PhysPhysliteProductionRun3.

General information on production

Production of PHYS and PHYSLITE formats

  • Following the ATLAS Run 3 computing model, the PHYS/PHYSLITE derivations are produced within the bulk production 3 to 4 times per year. The DAOD coordination team together with ADC, Software and Computing coordinators and Physics Coordination agree on the schedule for next production.
  • In every bulk production, all main data (Run 2 and Run 3) are produced. Standard Model MC Samples marked as "Baseline" and "Systematics" in the PMG Cental Page (mc20, mc23) are also produced centrally. Other MC samples have to be requested to the corresponding group derivation contacts.
  • Details on the latest bulk production can be found here: PhysPhysliteProductionRun3
  • Note that for newly produced mc20/mc23 MC samples, PHYS and PHYSLITE derivations are automatically produced as part of the MC production (for a given MC sample production, go to the production task page for the reconstruction step and look for 'Related requests'). Typically, MC production group sets this up while generating the samples. If there are some issues with the actual running of derivations, the derivations coordination team will handle this.

Production of non-PHYS formats

  • Preferable these formats will be produced in sync with the PHYS formats to avoid multiple stagings.
  • See next sub-section for instructions on how to request them.

How Do I Request Derivations production?

If you need PHYS/PHYSLITE derivations, make sure that for your samples, they are not already being produced as part of Run 3 model (see above section Production of PHYS and PHYSLITE formats)

  • DATA derivations are submitted by the group production managers ( atlas-phys-dpd-production).
    • For PHYS/PHYSLITE (and physics_Main stream), these are produced as part of the BULK production.
    • For non-PHYS/PHYSLITE formats or specific data stream (any format, including PHYS/PHYSLITE), please open a JIRA ticket here: ATLASDPD.
    • If you need a new R21/R25 release please ask your derivation group contact
    • Data period containers are created by the group derivation contacts (list below)

  • MC derivations
    • For group specific (non-PHYS/LITE) formats: these are submitted by the group derivation contacts
    • For PHYS and PHYSLITE formats:
      • SM samples marked as BASELINE and SYSTEMATICS samples in the PMG Central Page (mc20, mc23) are submitted by the group production managers (as part of the BULK production)
      • Specific (non-SM) signal samples and other SM samples (not marked as BASELINE or SYSTEMATICS) are submitted by the group derivation contacts (on demand)

Do You Need More Information on Derivations (e.g. coding, PHYS(LITE), ...)?

Meetings & mailing lists

  • DAOD production coordination meetings are on Wednesdays, 15:00 (CERN time). Please see: Indico.
  • Mailing lists: atlas-phys-dpd-coordination@cern.ch (for communication to DPD team), atlas-phys-dpd-production@cern.ch (for production issues)
  • General mailing list that includes derivation contacts and DAOD-interested people: atlas-comp-group-production@cern.ch.

R25 (Run 3)

  • Derivation software framework: DerivationFramework.
  • Adding a new PA format or requesting a change in PHYS/PHYSLITE? needs to be discussed with DAOD and AMG coordination. Contact atlas-phys-dpd-coordination and atlas-phys-amg-conveners (see below more specific details for PHYS and PHYSLITE only)
  • Disk space occupied by non PHYS/PHYSLITE formats (based on R21 derivations available): Google sheet.
  • The full list of ptags and patternIDs for Athena releases in R22+ is here: FullListOfPtagsAndPatternsR22

R21

  • Derivation software framework: DerivationFrameworkRun2.
  • Do you need to add a new format? --> contact atlas-phys-dpd-coordination
  • Information on TRUTH formats: TruthDAOD.
  • Disk space
    • DATA: Grafana plots
    • MC: Grafana plots
  • The full list of ptags and patternIDs for AthDerivation-21.2.X.Y: FullListOfPtagsAndPatterns

Data deletion policy for obsolete DAOD datasets

Please note that:

  • NB1: the DAOD obsolescence system is completely orthogonal to the DDM lifetime model! (more details on the DDM lifetime model here).
  • NB2: the DAOD DELETION IS NOT RUN AUTOMATICALLY! It is announced at the DAOD coordination meetings, and propagated to the groups by the derivation contacts.

For physics DAODs, the general policy is to retain only one version at once, per parent AOD. The version is defined by the cache - if a new DAOD is produced with a more recent cache, the existing DAOD with the older cache is regarded as obsolete and is subject to deletion, provided it has the same parent AOD as the newer version. If the parent AOD is different the two datasets can co-exist. Obsolete datasets are given a grace period of 60 days starting from the completion of the newer dataset.

For CP groups, two concurrent versions with the same AOD parent are allowed.

A list of obsolete datasets is maintained automatically here:

  • Data: https://prodtask-dev.cern.ch/ng/gp-stats?type=data
  • MC: https://prodtask-dev.cern.ch/ng/gp-stats?type=mc

The obsoleted datasets are labelled with three different colors:

  • Datasets in RED are overdue for deletion (they can be deleted any time). In reality the script generating the above pages does not delete anything - this is still done manually. Deletion is announced at the DAOD coordination meetings and by the derivation group contacts by email.
  • Datasets in ORANGE were declared obsolete <60 days ago (i.e. they are still in the grace period and they cannot be deleted yet, but they will become RED soon).
  • Datasets in GREEN are obsolete, but their lifetime have been extended.

--> When a deletion campaign is announced, all datasets labelled in RED and ORANGE need to have their lifetime extended if they are needed.

Groups can request prolongations of the lifetime of their obsolete datasets if they are still needed, by an extra 60 days (and further prolongations of the same length thereafter). You can also subscribe to the DAOD Removal Reminder to get weekly notifications about derivations marked for deletion (see below). The system allows to automatically extend the derivations lifetime!

Some instructions on how to use the new system can be found in these slides: DAOD_InstructionsObsolescence_03052022.pdf.

DAOD removal reminder emails

  • The DAOD removal reminder is a script which scans the dataset obsolescence and the dataset-beyond-lifetime lists for DAODs every night and sends emails to subscribers filtered for specific derivation formats. In case there are no differences w.r.t. the previous night found for a specific subscription the email is suppressed except for a reminder once a week.
  • If you would like to subscribe for one (or more formats), please use the subscription self-service repository at https://gitlab.cern.ch/wwalko/drrsubscriptions and follow the instructions in the README file.
  • You'll need to adjust the following information:
    • Your name(s) -- we can subscribe multiple people to the same selection at once
    • Your email address(es)
    • MC formats to watch (e.g. BPHYxx) -- may be a regular expression
    • Data formats to watch (e.g. BPHYxx) -- may be a regular expression
    • Number of days before expiration to include datasets (default: 14 days)
    • Name of the JIRA project for users to post exception requests to
  • The emails you will receive will contain an overview section as well as lists of datasets affected.
  • Example Example 
    Dear Wolfgang Walkowiak,

please see below for the list(s) of DAOD datasets scheduled for immediate
removal (IR), for removal after the expiration of the remaining grace period
(GP) or for removal due to dataset secondarization (SEC).  Datasets are
shown only if the remaining grace period is less than 15 days.

Summary:
  data  DAOD_BPHY8  IR:     0  GP:     0  SEC:     2 datasets
  mc    DAOD_BPHY8  IR:     0  GP:     0  SEC:     5 datasets

Your subscription(s) [WW01]:
  data         : BPHY8$
  mc           : BPHY8$
  Warnings for : < 15 days of grace period

Please check the following link(s) for more details:
  data         : http://adc-mon.cern.ch/DAODProduction//DAILYCHECK_DATA/
  mc           : http://adc-mon.cern.ch/DAODProduction//DAILYCHECK_MC/
  secondarized :
http://adc-mon.cern.ch/lifetime-model/results/latest/beyond-lifetime-centrally-managed/

Please post a ticket on the ATLBPHYS JIRA in case you want/need to extend
the grace period (possible by 60 days) for particular datasets.  Please
remember to provide a list of datasets concerned (no wildcards!) and a good
reason for the extension request.

Thank you for checking and best wishes,

DAOD Removal Reminder V0.3 by w.w.


Lists: (number of grace period days remaining / dataset name)

  • In case of issues or questions please contact Wolfgang Walkowiak via email.

Group contact MC DAOD production (EXPERTS ONLY!)

Instructions on how derivation group contacts can submit MC derivations can be found in this page.

Debug stream derivations in release 21.2

Debug stream derivations are produced on request together with main stream derivations (the p-tag is different from the data one since and additional setting is needed). The derivations are made period-by-period to avoid too many empty files. The naming convention is as follows: the run number of the container is the last run in the given period. The period name is added to the stream name (e.g. periodA_debugrec_hlt). The tags (except p-tag) correspond to the tags of the last run in the period.

Pileup Reweighting

The NTUP_PILEUP production is made automatically in the MC production chain after the AOD is merged (NB: if no merge step is submitted, no NTUP_PILEUP is produced). Please refer to the MC page Specific Information on MC campaigns for the most updated information and NTUP_PILEUP p-tags.

Description of DAOD coordination roles

(1) Derivations coordinator (1 person: estimated 0.3-0.4 FTE) - responsible for:

  • overall delivery of derived data formats to ATLAS
  • running the weekly DAOD production coordination meeting
  • organising open ended production and bulk processing campaigns
  • acting as the main contact person for all matters related to DAOD production
  • liaising with physics groups (via group contacts) with regards to the content and configuration of their formats
  • liaising with physics coordination with regards to the timescales for production, deletion policies, production priorities, AODFixes
  • liaising with computing coordination and ADC for matters related to DAOD production
  • liaising with data preparation with regards to input data
  • liaising with the reconstruction group with regards to AODFixes
  • overall size of the DAOD formats
  • CPU and memory performance of the derivation framework software
  • developing and managing DAOD deletion policies in consultation with the physics groups and relevant activity coordinators
  • definition of the ART nightly tests

(2) DAOD production managers (2 persons: estimated 0.2 FTE each) - responsible for (in collaboration with the derivations coordinator):

  • defining and supervising DAOD production tasks for data, and supervising MC tasks submitted by the groups
  • aborting and re-starting/re-assiging problematic tasks and adjusting priorities where necessary
  • attending the weekly DAOD production and ADC meetings to report on production news and problems
  • liaising with ADC where necessary, along with the DAOD coordinator

(3) AthDerivation release manager (1 person: estimated 0.1 FTE) - responsible for (in collaboration with the derivations coordinator):

  • monitoring, reviewing, prioritizing and accepting merge requests submitted to GitLab by the groups
  • liaise when necessary with the analysis release coordinators where a merge request could affect both
  • monitoring the nightly builds and ART tests and reporting problems
  • requesting AthDerivation cache builds
  • manually building patch caches
  • attending the weekly DAOD coordination (Wednesday 3pm), software coordination (Thursday 4pm) and ASG (Friday 2pm) meetings

Description of group contact roles

Group contacts are responsible for (within their respective group/format):

  • attending the weekly DAOD Coordination meetings (Wednesday 3pm) and give a short report on any software developments, production issues/plans or needs for new AthDerivation releases
  • collect production requests on MC from their group
  • submit MC derivation production
  • follow up on the MC production after submission and report/fix any issues
  • submit JIRA ticket to the DPDJira project requesting derivation production on data
  • being responsible for the daily ART tests (check that they're green) and check output in case bigger changes have been done
  • liaise with the dpd derivation team if a new AthDerivation cache is needed
  • keep track of their productions expiry date (i.e. when a certain ptag is no longer needed by the group) and notify the dpd coordination if old samples can be deleted
  • check that the data derivations requested meet their expectations in terms of content and quantity (all variables and events are present, all runs were processed)
  • create data containers for group formats

A list of things to consider when requesting or monitoring productions is in InfoForGroupContacts.pdf

2015, 2016 and 2017 data: re-derivation campaign in release 21.2

All data DAODs were re-run in 21.2 in November/December 2017. These datasets should be used for all physics analysis for non-2018 data. Three caches were used in this campaign. To see which cache your format was made with, please refer to the top of this JIRA ticket: https://its.cern.ch/jira/browse/ATLASDPD-997

For full information on the production, and MC request IDs, see the tables further down the page.

Cache Data p-tag MC (skim) p-tag MC (pass-through) p-tag
21.2.8.0 p3372 p3371 p3374
21.2.9.0 p3388 p3387 p3390
21.2.10.0 p3402 p3401 p3404
Responsible: Cristiano Alpigiani rev="1.1"
Last reviewed by: Never reviewed
